[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] For example, it is desired to estimate the proportion of a population of voters who will vote for a particular candidate.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] That proportion is the parameter sought; the estimate is based on a small random sample of voters.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] Alternatively, it is desired to estimate the probability of a voter voting for a particular candidate, based on some demographic features, such as age.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] Or, for example, in radar the aim is to find the range of objects (airplanes, boats, etc.) by analyzing the two-way transit timing of received echoes of transmitted pulses.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] Since the reflected pulses are unavoidably embedded in electrical noise, their measured values are randomly distributed, so that the transit time must be estimated.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] As another example, in electrical communication theory, the measurements which contain information regarding the parameters of interest are often associated with a noisy signal.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] For a given model, several statistical "ingredients" are needed so the estimator can be implemented.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] The first is a statistical sample – a set of data points taken from a random vector (RV) of size *N*.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] It is then necessary to define the Bayesian probability $\pi ({\boldsymbol {\theta }}).\,$ After the model is formed, the goal is to estimate the parameters, with the estimates commonly denoted ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\theta }}}$ , where the "hat" indicates the estimate.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] One common estimator is the minimum mean squared error (MMSE) estimator, which utilizes the error between the estimated parameters and the actual value of the parameters $\mathbf {e} ={\hat {\boldsymbol {\theta }}}-{\boldsymbol {\theta }}$ as the basis for optimality.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] This error term is then squared and the expected value of this squared value is minimized for the MMSE estimator.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] Consider a received discrete signal, $x[n]$ , of N independent samples that consists of an unknown constant A with additive white Gaussian noise (AWGN) $w[n]$ with zero mean and known variance $\sigma ^{2}$ (*i.e.*, ${\mathcal {N}}(0,\sigma ^{2})$ ).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] Since the variance is known then the only unknown parameter is A .
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] At this point, these two estimators would appear to perform the same.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] It would seem that the sample mean is a better estimator since its variance is lower for every *N* > 1.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] This results in the maximum likelihood estimator ${\hat {A}}={\frac {1}{N}}\sum _{n=0}^{N-1}x[n]$ which is simply the sample mean.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] From this example, it was found that the sample mean is the maximum likelihood estimator for N samples of a fixed, unknown parameter corrupted by AWGN.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] Comparing this to the variance of the sample mean (determined previously) shows that the sample mean is *equal to* the Cramér–Rao lower bound for all values of N and A .
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] In other words, the sample mean is the (necessarily unique) efficient estimator, and thus also the minimum variance unbiased estimator (MVUE), in addition to being the maximum likelihood estimator.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] One of the simplest non-trivial examples of estimation is the estimation of the maximum of a uniform distribution.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] It is used as a hands-on classroom exercise and to illustrate basic principles of estimation theory.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] Further, in the case of estimation based on a single sample, it demonstrates philosophical issues and possible misunderstandings in the use of maximum likelihood estimators and likelihood functions.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] Given a discrete uniform distribution $1,2,\dots ,N$ with unknown maximum, the UMVU estimator for the maximum is given by ${\frac {k+1}{k}}m-1=m+{\frac {m}{k}}-1$ where *m* is the sample maximum and *k* is the sample size, sampling without replacement.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] This problem is commonly known as the German tank problem, due to application of maximum estimation to estimates of German tank production during World War II.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] the gap being added to compensate for the negative bias of the sample maximum as an estimator for the population maximum.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] This has a variance of ${\frac {1}{k}}{\frac {(N-k)(N+1)}{(k+2)}}\approx {\frac {N^{2}}{k^{2}}}{\text{ for small samples }}k\ll N$ so a standard deviation of approximately $N/k$ , the (population) average size of a gap between samples; compare ${\frac {m}{k}}$ above.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] This can be seen as a very simple case of maximum spacing estimation.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] The sample maximum is the maximum likelihood estimator for the population maximum, but, as discussed above, it is biased.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] Numerous fields require the use of estimation theory.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/estimation-theory] Measured data are likely to be subject to noise or uncertainty and it is through statistical probability that optimal solutions are sought to extract as much information from the data as possible.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] A *property testing algorithm* for a decision problem is an algorithm whose query complexity (the number of queries made to its input) is much smaller than the instance size of the problem.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] Property testing algorithms are central to the definition of probabilistically checkable proofs, as a probabilistically checkable proof is essentially a proof that can be verified by a property testing algorithm.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] Here, "x is ε-far from L" means that the Hamming distance between x and any string in L is at least *ε* |*x*|.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] A property testing algorithm is said to have *one-sided error* if it satisfies the stronger condition that the accepting probability for instances *x* ∈ *L* is 1 instead of 2/3.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] A property testing algorithm is said be *non-adaptive* if it performs all its queries before it "observes" any answers to previous queries.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] Such an algorithm can be viewed as operating in the following manner.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] Before looking at the input, using its internal randomness, the algorithm decides which symbols of the input are to be queried.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] Next, the algorithm observes these symbols.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] Finally, without making any additional queries (but possibly using its randomness), the algorithm decides whether to accept or reject the input.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] The main efficiency parameter of a property testing algorithm is its query complexity, which is the maximum number of input symbols inspected over all inputs of a given length (and all random choices made by the algorithm).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] Computer scientists are interested in designing algorithms whose query complexity is as small as possible.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] In many cases, the running time of property testing algorithms is sublinear in the instance length.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] Typically, the goal is first to make the query complexity as small as possible as a function of the instance size n, and then study the dependency on the proximity parameter ε.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] Unlike other complexity-theoretic settings, the asymptotic query complexity of property testing algorithms is affected dramatically by the representation of instances.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] For example, when *ε* = 0.01, the problem of testing bipartiteness of *dense graphs* (which are represented by their adjacency matrix) admits an algorithm of constant query complexity.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] In contrast, sparse graphs on n vertices (which are represented by their adjacency list) require property testing algorithms of query complexity Ω(*n*1/2).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] The query complexity of property testing algorithms grows as the proximity parameter ε becomes smaller for all non-trivial properties.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] This dependence on ε is necessary, as a change of fewer than ε symbols in the input cannot be detected with constant probability using fewer than *O*(1/*ε*) queries.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] Many interesting properties of dense graphs can be tested using query complexity that depends only on ε and not on the graph size n.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] However, the query complexity can grow enormously fast as a function of ε.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] For example, for a long time, the best known algorithm for testing whether a graph does not contain any triangle had a query complexity which is a tower function of poly(1/*ε*), and only in 2010 was this improved to a tower function of log(1/*ε*).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] One of the reasons for this enormous growth in bounds is that many of the positive results for property testing of graphs are established using the Szemerédi regularity lemma, which also has tower-type bounds in its conclusions.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] The connection of property testing to the Szemerédi regularity lemma and related graph removal lemmas is elaborated on below.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] For a graph G with n vertices, the notion of distance we will use is the *edit distance*.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] That is, we say that the distance between two graphs is the smallest ε such that one can add and/or delete *εn*2 edges and get from the first graph to the second.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] Under a reasonable representation of graphs, this is equivalent to the earlier *Hamming distance* definition (up to possibly a change of constants).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] To make precise the general notions of property testing in the context of graphs, we say a tester for graph property P should distinguish with at least two-thirds probability between the cases of G satisfying P and the cases where G is ε-far in edit distance from satisfying P.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] The tester can access some oracle to query whether a pair of vertices has an edge between them in G or not.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] The *query complexity* is the number of such oracle queries.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] Say the tester has *one-sided error* if it has false positives and not false negatives, i.e. if G satisfies P, the tester always outputs the correct answer.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] We can only differentiate between graphs that satisfy P versus those far from P, as opposed to satisfying versus not satisfying P.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] In the latter case, consider two graphs: G satisfying P and H not satisfying P by changing only a few edges.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] One example is testing triangle-freeness with *H* a graph with exactly one triangle and G having one of these edges removed.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] Then, the tester cannot tell them apart unless it queries every edge, which it cannot do.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] The field of graph property testing was first introduced by Goldreich, Goldwasser, and Ron.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] In their seminal paper published in 1998, an abstract graph partition problem is analyzed and some testers provided.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] These include as special cases several important graph properties like bipartiteness, *k*-colorability, having a large clique, and having a large cut.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] In particular, the *natural* algorithms that sample a subgraph and check whether it satisfy the property are all correct, albeit with perhaps-suboptimal query complexities.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] A graph property is *hereditary* if it is preserved under deletion of vertices, or equivalently, if it is preserved under taking induced subgraphs.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] A few important hereditary properties are *H*-freeness (for some graph *H*), k-colorability, and planarity.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] Every hereditary graph property is testable with one-sided error.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] The proof relies on a version of the **graph removal lemma** for infinite families of induced subgraphs.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] The query complexity using this regularity approach is large due to the tower function bound in the **Szemerédi regularity lemma**.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] Informally, an *oblivious tester* is oblivious to the size of the input.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] For a graph property P, it is an algorithm that takes as input a parameter ε and graph G, and then runs as a property testing algorithm on G for the property P with proximity parameter ε that makes exactly *q*(*ε*) queries to G.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] Crucially, the number of queries an oblivious tester makes is a constant dependent only on ε and not the size of the input graph G.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] In complete analogy with property testing algorithms, we can talk about oblivious testers with one-sided error.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] We can contrive some graph properties for which a tester must access the number of vertices.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] In this case, the tester cannot even differentiate which property (bipartiteness or perfectness) to test unless it knows the number of vertices.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] There are many examples of such unnatural properties.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] In fact, the characterization of graph properties testable by an oblivious tester with one-sided error leads to a class of natural properties.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] Trivially, hereditary properties are also semi-hereditary.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] This characterization partially answers the converse to the other Alon & Shapira theorem above: the properties that are easy to test properties (having oblivious testers with one-sided error) are almost hereditary.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] In this section, we will give some *natural* oblivious testing algorithms with one-sided error for triangle-freeness, bipartiteness, and k-colorability.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] They are natural in the sense that we follow the natural idea of randomly sampling some subset X of vertices of *G* and checking whether the graph property holds on the subgraph spanned by *X* by brute-force search.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] We have one-sided error since these properties are actually hereditary: if *G* satisfy the property, so must the induced subgraph spanned by *X*, so our tester always accepts.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] For triangle-freeness, the tester is an application of the **triangle removal lemma**.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] In particular, it tells us that if graph *G* is ε-far from being triangle-free, then there is a (computable) constant *δ* = *δ*(*ε*) so that G has at least *δn*3 triangles.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] For bipartiteness and k-colorability, let δ be the desired upper bound on error probability for the following testers.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] Note that query complexity should not be confused with running time.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/property-testing] The latter is often exponential (as is the case of both) due to a lack of polynomial time decision algorithm to test the property on the induced subgraph.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In statistics, quality assurance, and survey methodology, **sampling** is the selection of a subset of individuals from within a statistical population to estimate characteristics of the whole population.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] The subset, called a **statistical sample** (or **sample**, for short), is meant to reflect the whole population, and statisticians attempt to collect samples that are representative of the population.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Sampling has lower costs and faster data collection compared to a census recording data from the entire population (in many cases, collecting the whole population is impossible, like getting sizes of all stars in the universe).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Thus, it can provide insights in cases where it is infeasible to measure an entire population.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Each observation measures one or more properties (such as weight, location, colour or mass) of independent objects or individuals.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In survey sampling, weights can be applied to the data to adjust for the sample design, particularly in stratified sampling.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Results from probability theory and statistical theory are employed to guide the practice.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In business and medical research, sampling is widely used for gathering information about a population.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Acceptance sampling is used to determine if a production lot of material meets the governing specifications.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Random sampling by using lots is an old idea, mentioned several times in the Bible.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In 1786, Pierre Simon Laplace estimated the population of France by using a sample, along with ratio estimator.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] He also computed probabilistic estimates of the error.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] These were not expressed as modern confidence intervals but as the sample size that would be needed to achieve a particular upper bound on the sampling error with probability 1000/1001.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] His estimates used Bayes' theorem with a uniform prior probability and assumed that his sample was random.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Alexander Ivanovich Chuprov introduced sample surveys to Imperial Russia in the 1870s.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In the US, the 1936 *Literary Digest* prediction of a Republican win in the presidential election went badly awry, due to severe bias [1].
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] More than two million people responded to the study with their names obtained through magazine subscription lists and telephone directories.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] It was not appreciated that these lists were heavily biased towards Republicans and the resulting sample, though very large, was deeply flawed.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Successful statistical practice is based on focused problem definition.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In sampling, this includes defining the "population" from which our sample is drawn.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] A population can be defined as including all people or items with the characteristics one wishes to understand.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Because there is very rarely enough time or money to gather information from everyone or everything in a population, the goal becomes finding a representative sample (or subset) of that population.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Sometimes what defines a population is obvious.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] For example, a manufacturer needs to decide whether a batch of material from production is of high enough quality to be released to the customer or should be scrapped or reworked due to poor quality.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In this case, the batch is the population.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Although the population of interest often consists of physical objects, sometimes it is necessary to sample over time, space, or some combination of these dimensions.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] For instance, an investigation of supermarket staffing could examine checkout line length at various times, or a study on endangered penguins might aim to understand their usage of various hunting grounds over time.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] For the time dimension, the focus may be on periods or discrete occasions.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In other cases, the examined 'population' may be even less tangible.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] For example, Joseph Jagger studied the behaviour of roulette wheels at a casino in Monte Carlo, and used this to identify a biased wheel.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In this case, the 'population' Jagger wanted to investigate was the overall behaviour of the wheel (i.e. the probability distribution of its results over infinitely many trials), while his 'sample' was formed from observed results from that wheel.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Similar considerations arise when taking repeated measurements of properties of materials such as the electrical conductivity of copper.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] This situation often arises when seeking knowledge about the cause system of which the *observed* population is an outcome.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In such cases, sampling theory may treat the observed population as a sample from a larger 'superpopulation'.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] For example, a researcher might study the success rate of a new 'quit smoking' program on a test group of 100 patients, in order to predict the effects of the program if it were made available nationwide.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Here the superpopulation is "everybody in the country, given access to this treatment" – a group that does not yet exist since the program is not yet available to all.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] The population from which the sample is drawn may not be the same as the population from which information is desired.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Often there is a large but not complete overlap between these two groups due to frame issues etc.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Sometimes they may be entirely separate – for instance, one might study rats in order to get a better understanding of human health, or one might study records from people born in 2008 in order to make predictions about people born in 2009.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Time spent in making the sampled population and population of concern precise is often well spent because it raises many issues, ambiguities, and questions that would otherwise have been overlooked at this stage.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In the most straightforward case, such as the sampling of a batch of material from production (acceptance sampling by lots), it would be most desirable to identify and measure every single item in the population and to include any one of them in our sample.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] However, in the more general case this is not usually possible or practical.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] There is no way to identify all rats in the set of all rats.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Where voting is not compulsory, there is no way to identify which people will vote at a forthcoming election (in advance of the election).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] These imprecise populations are not amenable to sampling in any of the ways below and to which we could apply statistical theory.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] As a remedy, we seek a sampling frame which has the property that we can identify every single element and include any in our sample.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] The most straightforward type of frame is a list of elements of the population (preferably the entire population) with appropriate contact information.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] For example, in an opinion poll, possible sampling frames include an electoral register and a telephone directory.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] A **probability sample** is a sample in which every unit in the population has a chance (greater than zero) of being selected in the sample, and this probability can be accurately determined.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] The combination of these traits makes it possible to produce unbiased estimates of population totals, by weighting sampled units according to their probability of selection.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In the above example, not everybody has the same probability of selection; what makes it a probability sample is the fact that each person's probability is known.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] When every element in the population *does* have the same probability of selection, this is known as an 'equal probability of selection' (EPS) design.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Such designs are also referred to as 'self-weighting' because all sampled units are given the same weight.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Probability sampling includes: simple random sampling, systematic sampling, stratified sampling, probability-proportional-to-size sampling, and cluster or multistage sampling.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] 2. involves random selection at some point.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Nonprobability sampling methods include convenience sampling, quota sampling, snowball sampling, and purposive sampling.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In addition, nonresponse effects may turn *any* probability design into a nonprobability design if the characteristics of nonresponse are not well understood, since nonresponse effectively modifies each element's probability of being sampled.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Within any of the types of frames identified above, a variety of sampling methods can be employed individually or in combination.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In a simple random sample (SRS) of a given size, all subsets of a sampling frame have an equal probability of being selected.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Each element of the frame thus has an equal probability of selection: the frame is not subdivided or partitioned.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Furthermore, any given *pair* of elements has the same chance of selection as any other such pair (and similarly for triples, and so on).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] This minimizes bias and simplifies analysis of results.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In particular, the variance between individual results within the sample is a good indicator of variance in the overall population, which makes it relatively easy to estimate the accuracy of results.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Simple random sampling can be vulnerable to sampling error because the randomness of the selection may result in a sample that does not reflect the makeup of the population.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] For instance, a simple random sample of ten people from a given country will *on average* produce five men and five women, but any given trial is likely to overrepresent one sex and underrepresent the other.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Systematic and stratified techniques attempt to overcome this problem by "using information about the population" to choose a more "representative" sample.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Also, simple random sampling can be cumbersome and tedious when sampling from a large target population.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In some cases, investigators are interested in research questions specific to subgroups of the population.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] For example, researchers might be interested in examining whether cognitive ability as a predictor of job performance is equally applicable across racial groups.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Simple random sampling cannot accommodate the needs of researchers in this situation, because it does not provide subsamples of the population, and other sampling strategies, such as stratified sampling, can be used instead.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Systematic sampling (also known as interval sampling) relies on arranging the study population according to some ordering scheme, and then selecting elements at regular intervals through that ordered list.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Systematic sampling involves a random start and then proceeds with the selection of every *k*th element from then onwards.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In this case, *k*=(population size/sample size).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] It is important that the starting point is not automatically the first in the list, but is instead randomly chosen from within the first to the *k*th element in the list.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] A simple example would be to select every 10th name from the telephone directory (an 'every 10th' sample, also referred to as 'sampling with a skip of 10').
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] As long as the starting point is randomized, systematic sampling is a type of probability sampling.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] It is easy to implement and the stratification induced can make it efficient, *if* the variable by which the list is ordered is correlated with the variable of interest.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] 'Every 10th' sampling is especially useful for efficient sampling from databases.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] For example, suppose we wish to sample people from a long street that starts in a poor area (house No.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] 1) and ends in an expensive district (house No.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] A simple random selection of addresses from this street could easily end up with too many from the high end and too few from the low end (or vice versa), leading to an unrepresentative sample.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Selecting (e.g.) every 10th street number along the street ensures that the sample is spread evenly along the length of the street, representing all of these districts.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] However, systematic sampling is especially vulnerable to periodicities in the list.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] If periodicity is present and the period is a multiple or factor of the interval used, the sample is especially likely to be *un*representative of the overall population, making the scheme less accurate than simple random sampling.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] For example, consider a street where the odd-numbered houses are all on the north (expensive) side of the road, and the even-numbered houses are all on the south (cheap) side.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Another drawback of systematic sampling is that even in scenarios where it is more accurate than SRS, its theoretical properties make it difficult to *quantify* that accuracy.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] As described above, systematic sampling is an EPS method, because all elements have the same probability of selection (in the example given, one in ten).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] It is *not* 'simple random sampling' because different subsets of the same size have different selection probabilities – e.g., the set {4,14,24,...,994} has a one-in-ten probability of selection, but the set {4,13,24,34,...} has zero probability of selection.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Systematic sampling can also be adapted to a non-EPS approach; for an example, see discussion of PPS samples below.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] When the population embraces a number of distinct categories, the frame can be organized by these categories into separate "strata." Each stratum is then sampled as an independent sub-population, out of which individual elements can be randomly selected.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] The ratio of the size of this random selection (or sample) to the size of the population is called a sampling fraction.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] There are several potential benefits to stratified sampling.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] First, dividing the population into distinct, independent strata can enable researchers to draw inferences about specific subgroups that may be lost in a more generalized random sample.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Second, utilizing a stratified sampling method can lead to more efficient statistical estimates (provided that strata are selected based upon relevance to the criterion in question, instead of availability of the samples).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Even if a stratified sampling approach does not lead to increased statistical efficiency, such a tactic will not result in less efficiency than would simple random sampling, provided that each stratum is proportional to the group's size in the population.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Finally, since each stratum is treated as an independent population, different sampling approaches can be applied to different strata, potentially enabling researchers to use the approach best suited (or most cost-effective) for each identified subgroup within the population.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] There are, however, some potential drawbacks to using stratified sampling.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] First, identifying strata and implementing such an approach can increase the cost and complexity of sample selection, as well as leading to increased complexity of population estimates.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Second, when examining multiple criteria, stratifying variables may be related to some, but not to others, further complicating the design, and potentially reducing the utility of the strata.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] The variables upon which the population is stratified are strongly correlated with the desired dependent variable.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Allows use of different sampling techniques for different subpopulations.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Improves the accuracy/efficiency of estimation.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Permits greater balancing of statistical power of tests of differences between strata by sampling equal numbers from strata varying widely in size.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Is not useful when there are no homogeneous subgroups.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Stratification is sometimes introduced after the sampling phase in a process called "poststratification".
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] This approach is typically implemented due to a lack of prior knowledge of an appropriate stratifying variable or when the experimenter lacks the necessary information to create a stratifying variable during the sampling phase.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Although the method is susceptible to the pitfalls of post hoc approaches, it can provide several benefits in the right situation.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Implementation usually follows a simple random sample.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In addition to allowing for stratification on an ancillary variable, poststratification can be used to implement weighting, which can improve the precision of a sample's estimates.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Choice-based sampling or oversampling is one of the stratified sampling strategies.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In choice-based sampling, the data are stratified on the target and a sample is taken from each stratum so that rarer target classes will be more represented in the sample.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] The model is then built on this biased sample.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] The effects of the input variables on the target are often estimated with more precision with the choice-based sample even when a smaller overall sample size is taken, compared to a random sample.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] The results usually must be adjusted to correct for the oversampling.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In some cases the sample designer has access to an "auxiliary variable" or "size measure", believed to be correlated to the variable of interest, for each element in the population.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] These data can be used to improve accuracy in sample design.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] One option is to use the auxiliary variable as a basis for stratification, as discussed above.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Another option is probability proportional to size ('PPS') sampling, in which the selection probability for each element is set to be proportional to its size measure, up to a maximum of 1.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In a simple PPS design, these selection probabilities can then be used as the basis for Poisson sampling.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] However, this has the drawback of variable sample size, and different portions of the population may still be over- or under-represented due to chance variation in selections.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Systematic sampling theory can be used to create a probability proportionate to size sample.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] This is done by treating each count within the size variable as a single sampling unit.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Samples are then identified by selecting at even intervals among these counts within the size variable.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] This method is sometimes called PPS-sequential or monetary unit sampling in the case of audits or forensic sampling.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] The PPS approach can improve accuracy for a given sample size by concentrating sample on large elements that have the greatest impact on population estimates.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] PPS sampling is commonly used for surveys of businesses, where element size varies greatly and auxiliary information is often available – for instance, a survey attempting to measure the number of guest-nights spent in hotels might use each hotel's number of rooms as an auxiliary variable.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In some cases, an older measurement of the variable of interest can be used as an auxiliary variable when attempting to produce more current estimates.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Sometimes it is more cost-effective to select respondents in groups ('clusters').
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Sampling is often clustered by geography or by time periods (nearly all samples are in some sense 'clustered' in time – although this is rarely taken into account in the analysis).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] For instance, if surveying households within a city, we might choose to select 100 city blocks and then interview every household within the selected blocks.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Clustering can reduce travel and administrative costs.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In the example above, an interviewer can make a single trip to visit several households in one block, rather than having to drive to a different block for each household.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] It also means that one does not need a sampling frame listing all elements in the target population.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Instead, clusters can be chosen from a cluster-level frame, with an element-level frame created only for the selected clusters.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In the example above, the sample only requires a block-level city map for initial selections, and then a household-level map of the 100 selected blocks, rather than a household-level map of the whole city.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Cluster sampling (also known as clustered sampling) generally increases the variability of sample estimates above that of simple random sampling, depending on how the clusters differ between one another as compared to the within-cluster variation.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] For this reason, cluster sampling requires a larger sample than SRS to achieve the same level of accuracy – but cost savings from clustering might still make this a cheaper option.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Cluster sampling is commonly implemented as multistage sampling.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] This is a complex form of cluster sampling in which two or more levels of units are embedded one in the other.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] The first stage consists of constructing the clusters that will be used to sample from.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In the second stage, a sample of primary units is randomly selected from each cluster (rather than using all units contained in all selected clusters).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In following stages, in each of those selected clusters, additional samples of units are selected, and so on.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] All ultimate units (individuals, for instance) selected at the last step of this procedure are then surveyed.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] This technique, thus, is essentially the process of taking random subsamples of preceding random samples.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Multistage sampling can substantially reduce sampling costs, where the complete population list would need to be constructed (before other sampling methods could be applied).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] By eliminating the work involved in describing clusters that are not selected, multistage sampling can reduce the large costs associated with traditional cluster sampling.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] However, each sample may not be a full representative of the whole population.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In *quota sampling*, the population is first segmented into mutually exclusive sub-groups, just as in stratified sampling.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Then judgement is used to select the subjects or units from each segment based on a specified proportion.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] For example, an interviewer may be told to sample 200 females and 300 males between the age of 45 and 60.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] It is this second step which makes the technique one of nonprobability sampling.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In quota sampling the selection of the sample is non-random.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] For example, interviewers might be tempted to interview those who look most helpful.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] The problem is that these samples may be biased because not everyone gets a chance of selection.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] This random element is its greatest weakness and quota versus probability has been a matter of controversy for several years.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In imbalanced datasets, where the sampling ratio does not follow the population statistics, one can resample the dataset in a conservative manner called minimax sampling.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] The minimax sampling has its origin in Anderson minimax ratio whose value is proved to be 0.5: in a binary classification, the class-sample sizes should be chosen equally.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] This ratio can be proved to be minimax ratio only under the assumption of LDA classifier with Gaussian distributions.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] The notion of minimax sampling is recently developed for a general class of classification rules, called class-wise smart classifiers.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In this case, the sampling ratio of classes is selected so that the worst case classifier error over all the possible population statistics for class prior probabilities, would be the best.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Accidental sampling (sometimes known as **grab**, **convenience**, or **opportunity sampling**) is a type of nonprobability sampling which involves the sample being drawn from that part of the population which is close to hand.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] That is, a population is selected because it is readily available and convenient.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] It may be through meeting the person or including a person in the sample when one meets them or chosen by finding them through technological means such as the internet or through phone.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] The researcher using such a sample cannot scientifically make generalizations about the total population from this sample because it would not be representative enough.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] This type of sampling is most useful for pilot testing.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Is there good reason to believe that a particular convenience sample would or should respond or behave differently than a random sample from the same population?
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Is the question being asked by the research one that can adequately be answered using a convenience sample?
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In social science research, snowball sampling is a similar technique, where existing study subjects are used to recruit more subjects into the sample.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Some variants of snowball sampling, such as respondent driven sampling, allow calculation of selection probabilities and are probability sampling methods under certain conditions.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] The voluntary sampling method is a type of nonprobability sampling.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Volunteers may be invited through advertisements in social media.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] The target population for advertisements can be selected by characteristics like location, age, sex, income, occupation, education, or interests using tools provided by the social medium.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] The advertisement may include a message about the research and link to a survey.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] After following the link and completing the survey, the volunteer submits the data to be included in the sample population.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] This method can reach a global population but is limited by the campaign budget.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Volunteers outside the invited population may also be included in the sample.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] It is difficult to make generalizations from this sample because it may not represent the total population.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Often, volunteers have a strong interest in the main topic of the survey.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Line-intercept sampling is a method of sampling elements in a region whereby an element is sampled if a chosen line segment, called a "transect", intersects the element.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Snowball sampling involves finding a small group of initial respondents and using them to recruit more respondents.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] It is particularly useful in cases where the population is hidden or difficult to enumerate.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Theoretical sampling occurs when samples are selected on the basis of the results of the data collected so far with a goal of developing a deeper understanding of the area or develop theories.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] An initial, general sample is first collected with the goal of investigating general trends, where further sampling may consist of extreme or very specific cases might be selected in order to maximize the likelihood a phenomenon will actually be observable.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In active sampling, the samples which are used for training a machine learning algorithm are actively selected, also compare active learning (machine learning).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Judgement sampling, also known as expert or purposive sampling, is a type of non-random sampling where samples are selected based on the opinion of an expert, who can select participants based on how valuable the information they provide is.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Haphazard sampling refers to the idea of using human judgement to simulate randomness.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Despite samples being hand-picked, the goal is to ensure that no conscious bias exists within the choice of samples, but often fails due to selection bias.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Haphazard sampling is generally opted for due to its convenience, when the tools or capacity to perform other sampling methods may not exist.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] The major weakness of such samples is that they often do not represent the characteristics of the entire population, but just a segment of the population.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Because of this unbalanced representation, results from haphazard sampling are often biased.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Sampling schemes may be *without replacement* ('WOR' – no element can be selected more than once in the same sample) or *with replacement* ('WR' – an element may appear multiple times in the one sample).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] For example, if we catch fish, measure them, and immediately return them to the water before continuing with the sample, this is a WR design, because we might end up catching and measuring the same fish more than once.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] However, if we do not return the fish to the water or tag and release each fish after catching it, this becomes a WOR design.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Formulas, tables, and power function charts are well known approaches to determine sample size.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Locate the column corresponding to the estimated effect size.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] The intersection of the column and row is the minimum sample size required.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Sampling enables the selection of right data points from within the larger data set to estimate the characteristics of the whole population.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] For example, there are about 600 million tweets produced every day.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] It is not necessary to look at all of them to determine the topics that are discussed during the day, nor is it necessary to look at all the tweets to determine the sentiment on each of the topics.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] A theoretical formulation for sampling Twitter data has been developed.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In manufacturing different types of sensory data such as acoustics, vibration, pressure, current, voltage, and controller data are available at short time intervals.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] To predict down-time it may not be necessary to look at all the data but a sample may be sufficient.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Survey results are typically subject to some error.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Total errors can be classified into sampling errors and non-sampling errors.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] The term "error" here includes systematic biases as well as random errors.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Sampling errors and biases are induced by the sample design.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Random sampling error: Random variation in the results due to the elements in the sample being selected at random.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Non-sampling errors are other errors which can impact final survey estimates, caused by problems in data collection, processing, or sample design.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Under-coverage: sampling frame does not include elements in the population.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] After sampling, a review is held of the exact process followed in sampling, rather than that intended, in order to study any effects that any divergences might have on subsequent analysis.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] A particular problem involves *non-response*.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In survey sampling, many of the individuals identified as part of the sample may be unwilling to participate, not have the time to participate (opportunity cost), or survey administrators may not have been able to contact them.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In this case, there is a risk of differences between respondents and nonrespondents, leading to biased estimates of population parameters.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] This is often addressed by improving survey design, offering incentives, and conducting follow-up studies which make a repeated attempt to contact the unresponsive and to characterize their similarities and differences with the rest of the frame.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] The effects can also be mitigated by weighting the data (when population benchmarks are available) or by imputing data based on answers to other questions.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Nonresponse is particularly a problem in internet sampling.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Reasons for this problem may include improperly designed surveys, over-surveying (or survey fatigue), and the fact that potential participants may have multiple e-mail addresses, which they do not use anymore or do not check regularly.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] In many situations, the sample fraction may be varied by stratum and data will have to be weighted to correctly represent the population.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Thus for example, a simple random sample of individuals in the United Kingdom might not include some in remote Scottish islands who would be inordinately expensive to sample.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] A cheaper method would be to use a stratified sample with urban and rural strata.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] The rural sample could be under-represented in the sample, but weighted up appropriately in the analysis to compensate.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] More generally, data should usually be weighted if the sample design does not give each individual an equal chance of being selected.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] For instance, when households have equal selection probabilities but one person is interviewed from within each household, this gives people from large households a smaller chance of being interviewed.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] This can be accounted for using survey weights.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Similarly, households with more than one telephone line have a greater chance of being selected in a random digit dialing sample, and weights can adjust for this.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sampling-statistics] Weights can also serve other purposes, such as helping to correct for non-response.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sublinear-function] In linear algebra, a **sublinear** function (or functional as is more often used in functional analysis), also called a **quasi-seminorm**, on a vector space is a real-valued function with some of the properties of a seminorm.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sublinear-function] Unlike seminorms, a sublinear function does not have to be nonnegative-valued and also does not have to be absolutely homogeneous.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sublinear-function] Seminorms are themselves abstractions of the more well known notion of norms, where a seminorm has all the defining properties of a norm *except* that it is not required to map non-zero vectors to non-zero values.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sublinear-function] In functional analysis the name **Banach functional** is sometimes used, reflecting that they are most commonly used when applying a general formulation of the Hahn–Banach theorem.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sublinear-function] The notion of a sublinear function was introduced by Stefan Banach when he proved the Hahn-Banach theorem.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sublinear-function] A function $p:X\to \mathbb {R}$ is called *positive* or *nonnegative* if $p(x)\geq 0$ for all $x\in X,$ although some authors define *positive* to instead mean that $p(x)\neq 0$ whenever $x\neq 0;$ these definitions are not equivalent.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sublinear-function] It is a *symmetric function* if $p(-x)=p(x)$ for all $x\in X.$ Every subadditive symmetric function is necessarily nonnegative.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sublinear-function] A sublinear function on a real vector space is symmetric if and only if it is a seminorm.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sublinear-function] The set of all sublinear functions on $X,$ denoted by $X^{\#},$ can be partially ordered by declaring $p\leq q$ if and only if $p(x)\leq q(x)$ for all $x\in X.$ A sublinear function is called **minimal** if it is a minimal element of $X^{\#}$ under this order.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sublinear-function] A sublinear function is minimal if and only if it is a real linear functional.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sublinear-function] Every norm, seminorm, and real linear functional is a sublinear function.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sublinear-function] A function $p\colon X\to \mathbb {R}$ which is subadditive, convex, and satisfies $p(0)\leq 0$ is also positively homogeneous (the latter condition $p(0)\leq 0$ is necessary as the example of $p(x)={\sqrt {x^{2}+1}}$ on $X=\mathbb {R}$ shows).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sublinear-function] If p is positively homogeneous, it is convex if and only if it is subadditive.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sublinear-function] Therefore, assuming $p(0)\leq 0$ , any two properties among subadditivity, convexity, and positive homogeneity implies the third.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sublinear-function] If X is a real TVS, f is a linear functional on $X,$ and p is a continuous sublinear function on $X,$ then $f\leq p$ on X implies that f is continuous.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sublinear-function] Let V be an open convex subset of $X.$ If $0\in V$ then let $z:=0$ and otherwise let $z\in V$ be arbitrary.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sublinear-function] Let $p:X\to [0,\infty )$ be the Minkowski functional of $V-z,$ which is a continuous sublinear function on X since $V-z$ is convex, absorbing, and open ( p however is not necessarily a seminorm since V was not assumed to be balanced).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sublinear-function] The concept can be extended to operators that are homogeneous and subadditive.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sublinear-function] This requires only that the codomain be, say, an ordered vector space to make sense of the conditions.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sublinear-function] In computer science, a function $f:\mathbb {Z} ^{+}\to \mathbb {R}$ is called **sublinear** if $\lim _{n\to \infty }{\frac {f(n)}{n}}=0,$ or $f(n)\in o(n)$ in asymptotic notation (notice the small o ).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sublinear-function] Formally, $f(n)\in o(n)$ if and only if, for any given $c>0,$ there exists an N such that $f(n)<cn$ for $n\geq N.$ That is, f grows slower than any linear function.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/sublinear-function] The two meanings should not be confused: while a Banach functional is convex, almost the opposite is true for functions of sublinear growth: every function $f(n)\in o(n)$ can be upper-bounded by a concave function of sublinear growth.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] In theoretical computer science, the **time complexity** is the computational complexity that describes the amount of computer time it takes to run an algorithm.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Time complexity is commonly estimated by counting the number of elementary operations performed by the algorithm, supposing that each elementary operation takes a fixed amount of time to perform.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Thus, the amount of time taken and the number of elementary operations performed by the algorithm are taken to be related by a constant factor.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Since an algorithm's running time may vary among different inputs of the same size, one commonly considers the worst-case time complexity, which is the maximum amount of time required for inputs of a given size.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Less common, and usually specified explicitly, is the average-case complexity, which is the average of the time taken on inputs of a given size (this makes sense because there are only a finite number of possible inputs of a given size).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] In both cases, the time complexity is generally expressed as a function of the size of the input.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Since this function is generally difficult to compute exactly, and the running time for small inputs is usually not consequential, one commonly focuses on the behavior of the complexity when the input size increases—that is, the asymptotic behavior of the complexity.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Therefore, the time complexity is commonly expressed using big O notation, typically $O(n)$ , $O(n\log n)$ , $O(n^{\alpha })$ , $O(2^{n})$ , etc., where n is the size in units of bits needed to represent the input.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Algorithmic complexities are classified according to the type of function appearing in the big O notation.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] For example, an algorithm with time complexity $O(n)$ is a *linear time algorithm* and an algorithm with time complexity $O(n^{\alpha })$ for some constant $\alpha >0$ is a *polynomial time algorithm*.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] The following table summarizes some classes of commonly encountered time complexities.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is termed **constant time** (often represented as ${\textstyle O(1)}$ time) when its complexity function ${\textstyle T(n)}$ is bounded by a value that does not change with the size of the input.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] This implies that the execution time remains consistent regardless of how much data is processed.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] For instance, accessing a specific element in an array is a constant-time operation, as it requires only a single operation to locate that element.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] In contrast, determining the minimum value in an unordered array is not constant time; it requires examining each element, resulting in linear time complexity, or ${\textstyle O(n)}$ .
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] However, if the number of elements is known and fixed, certain tasks can still be considered constant time.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Importantly, the term "constant time" does not mean the running time must be entirely independent of the problem size; rather, it should have a consistent upper bound irrespective of input size.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] For example, a task that involves swapping the values of a and b to ensure ${\textstyle a\leq b}$ is classified as constant time, even if the execution time may vary depending on whether the condition is already met.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] The key is that there exists a constant t such that the time taken will never exceed t, regardless of the input values.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Constant-time algorithms are especially significant in contexts like cryptography, where timing attacks can exploit variations in execution time.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] By designing algorithms that run in constant time, developers can enhance security and ensure performance predictability, making it a fundamental consideration in software engineering.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to take **logarithmic time** when $T(n)=O(\log n)$ .
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Since $\log _{a}n$ and $\log _{b}n$ are related by a constant multiplier, and such a multiplier is irrelevant to big O classification, the standard usage for logarithmic-time algorithms is $O(\log n)$ regardless of the base of the logarithm appearing in the expression of T.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Algorithms taking logarithmic time are commonly found in operations on binary trees or when using binary search.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] An $O(\log n)$ algorithm is considered highly efficient, as the ratio of the number of operations to the size of the input decreases and tends to zero when n increases.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm that must access all elements of its input cannot take logarithmic time, as the time taken for reading an input of size n is of the order of n.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] An example of logarithmic time is given by dictionary search.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Consider a dictionary *D* which contains n entries, sorted in alphabetical order.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] We suppose that, for $1\leq k\leq n$ , one may access the kth entry of the dictionary in a constant time.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Under these hypotheses, the test to see if a word w is in the dictionary may be done in logarithmic time: consider $D\left(\left\lfloor {\frac {n}{2}}\right\rfloor \right)$ , where $\lfloor \;\rfloor$ denotes the floor function.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] If $w=D\left(\left\lfloor {\frac {n}{2}}\right\rfloor \right)$ --that is to say, the word w is exactly in the middle of the dictionary--then we are done.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Otherwise, if it comes after the middle word, continue similarly with the right half of the dictionary.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] This algorithm is similar to the method often used to find an entry in a paper dictionary.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] As a result, the search space within the dictionary decreases as the algorithm gets closer to the target word.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to run in **polylogarithmic time** if its time $T(n)$ is $O{\bigl (}(\log n)^{k}{\bigr )}$ for some constant k.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Another way to write this is $O(\log ^{k}n)$ .
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] For example, matrix chain ordering can be solved in polylogarithmic time on a parallel random-access machine, and a graph can be determined to be planar in a fully dynamic way in $O(\log ^{3}n)$ time per insert/delete operation.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to run in **sub-linear time** (often spelled **sublinear time**) if $T(n)=o(n)$ .
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] In particular this includes algorithms with the time complexities defined above.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] The specific term *sublinear time algorithm* commonly refers to randomized algorithms that sample a small fraction of their inputs and process them efficiently to approximately infer properties of the entire instance.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] This type of sublinear time algorithm is closely related to property testing and statistics.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to take **linear time**, or $O(n)$ time, if its time complexity is $O(n)$ .
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Informally, this means that the running time increases at most linearly with the size of the input.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] More precisely, this means that there is a constant c such that the running time is at most $cn$ for every input of size n.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] For example, a procedure that adds up all elements of a list requires time proportional to the length of the list, if the adding time is constant, or, at least, bounded by a constant.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Linear time is the best possible time complexity in situations where the algorithm has to sequentially read its entire input.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Therefore, much research has been invested into discovering algorithms exhibiting linear time or, at least, nearly linear time.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] This research includes both software and hardware methods.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] There are several hardware technologies which exploit parallelism to provide this.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] An example is content-addressable memory.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] This concept of linear time is used in string matching algorithms such as the Boyer–Moore string-search algorithm and Ukkonen's algorithm.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to run in **quasilinear time** (also referred to as **log-linear time**) if $T(n)=O(n\log ^{k}n)$ for some positive constant k; **linearithmic time** is the case $k=1$ .
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Using soft O notation these algorithms are ${\tilde {O}}(n)$ .
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Quasilinear time algorithms are also $O(n^{1+\varepsilon })$ for every constant $\varepsilon >0$ and thus run faster than any polynomial time algorithm whose time bound includes a term $n^{c}$ for any $c>1$ .
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] In many cases, the $O(n\log n)$ running time is simply the result of performing a $\Theta (\log n)$ operation n times (for the notation, see Big O notation § Family of Bachmann–Landau notations).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] For example, binary tree sort creates a binary tree by inserting each element of the n-sized array one by one.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Since the insert operation on a self-balancing binary search tree takes $O(\log n)$ time, the entire algorithm takes $O(n\log n)$ time.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Comparison sorts require at least $\Omega (n\log n)$ comparisons in the worst case because $\log(n!)=\Theta (n\log n)$ , by Stirling's approximation.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] They also frequently arise from the recurrence relation ${\textstyle T(n)=2T\left({\frac {n}{2}}\right)+O(n)}$ .
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be **subquadratic time** if $T(n)=o(n^{2})$ .
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] For example, simple, comparison-based sorting algorithms are quadratic (e.g. insertion sort), but more advanced algorithms can be found that are subquadratic (e.g. shell sort).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] No general-purpose sorts run in linear time, but the change from quadratic to sub-quadratic is of great practical importance.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be of **polynomial time** if its running time is upper bounded by a polynomial expression in the size of the input for the algorithm, that is, *T*(*n*) = *O*(*n**k*) for some positive constant *k*.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Problems for which a deterministic polynomial-time algorithm exists belong to the complexity class **P**, which is central in the field of computational complexity theory.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Cobham's thesis states that polynomial time is a synonym for "tractable", "feasible", "efficient", or "fast".
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] These two concepts are only relevant if the inputs to the algorithms consist of integers.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] The concept of polynomial time leads to several complexity classes in computational complexity theory.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Some important classes defined using polynomial time are the following.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] P is the smallest time-complexity class on a deterministic machine which is robust in terms of machine model changes.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is defined to take **superpolynomial time** if *T*(*n*) is not bounded above by any polynomial; that is, if ⁠ $T(n)\not \in O(n^{c})$ ⁠ for every positive integer *c*.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] For example, an algorithm that runs for 2*n* steps on an input of size *n* requires superpolynomial time (more specifically, exponential time).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm that uses exponential resources is clearly superpolynomial, but some algorithms are only very weakly superpolynomial.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] For example, the Adleman–Pomerance–Rumely primality test runs for *n**O*(log log *n*) time on *n*-bit inputs; this grows faster than any polynomial for large enough *n*, but the input size must become impractically large before it cannot be dominated by a polynomial with small degree.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm that requires superpolynomial time lies outside the complexity class **P**.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Cobham's thesis posits that these algorithms are impractical, and in many cases they are.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Since the P versus NP problem is unresolved, it is unknown whether NP-complete problems require superpolynomial time.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] There are some problems for which we know quasi-polynomial time algorithms, but no polynomial time algorithm is known.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Other computational problems with quasi-polynomial time solutions but no known polynomial time solution include the planted clique problem in which the goal is to find a large clique in the union of a clique and a random graph.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] The complexity class **QP** consists of all problems that have quasi-polynomial time algorithms.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] It can be defined in terms of DTIME as follows.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] In complexity theory, the unsolved P versus NP problem asks if all problems in NP have polynomial-time algorithms.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] All the best-known algorithms for NP-complete problems like 3SAT etc. take exponential time.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Indeed, it is conjectured for many natural NP-complete problems that they do not have sub-exponential time algorithms.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Here "sub-exponential time" is taken to mean the second definition presented below.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] (On the other hand, many graph problems represented in the natural way by adjacency matrices are solvable in subexponential time simply because the size of the input is the square of the number of vertices.) This conjecture (for the k-SAT problem) is known as the exponential time hypothesis.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Since it is conjectured that NP-complete problems do not have quasi-polynomial time algorithms, some inapproximability results in the field of approximation algorithms make the assumption that NP-complete problems do not have quasi-polynomial time algorithms.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] For example, see the known inapproximability results for the set cover problem.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] The term **sub-exponential time** is used to express that the running time of some algorithm may grow faster than any polynomial but is still significantly smaller than an exponential.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] In this sense, problems that have sub-exponential time algorithms are somewhat more tractable than those that only have exponential algorithms.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] The precise definition of "sub-exponential" is not generally agreed upon, however the two most widely used are below.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] A problem is said to be sub-exponential time solvable if it can be solved in running times whose logarithms grow smaller than any given polynomial.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] More precisely, a problem is in sub-exponential time if for every *ε* > 0 there exists an algorithm which solves the problem in time *O*(2*n**ε*).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] The set of all such problems is the complexity class **SUBEXP** which can be defined in terms of DTIME as follows.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] This notion of sub-exponential is non-uniform in terms of *ε* in the sense that *ε* is not part of the input and each ε may have its own algorithm for the problem.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Some authors define sub-exponential time as running times in $2^{o(n)}$ .
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] This definition allows larger running times than the first definition of sub-exponential time.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] An example of such a sub-exponential time algorithm is the best-known classical algorithm for integer factorization, the general number field sieve, which runs in time about $2^{{O}(n^{1/3}(\log n)^{2/3})}$ , where the length of the input is n.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Another example was the graph isomorphism problem, which the best known algorithm from 1982 to 2016 solved in $2^{O\left({\sqrt {n\log n}}\right)}$ .
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] However, at STOC 2016 a quasi-polynomial time algorithm was presented.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] It makes a difference whether the algorithm is allowed to be sub-exponential in the size of the instance, the number of vertices, or the number of edges.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] In parameterized complexity, this difference is made explicit by considering pairs $(L,k)$ of decision problems and parameters *k*.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] More precisely, SUBEPT is the class of all parameterized problems $(L,k)$ for which there is a computable function $f:\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {N}$ with $f\in o(k)$ and an algorithm that decides *L* in time $2^{f(k)}\cdot {\textsf {poly}}(n)$ .
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] The **exponential time hypothesis** (**ETH**) is that 3SAT, the satisfiability problem of Boolean formulas in conjunctive normal form with at most three literals per clause and with *n* variables, cannot be solved in time 2*o*(*n*).
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] More precisely, the hypothesis is that there is some absolute constant *c* > 0 such that 3SAT cannot be decided in time 2*cn* by any deterministic Turing machine.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] With *m* denoting the number of clauses, ETH is equivalent to the hypothesis that *k*SAT cannot be solved in time 2*o*(*m*) for any integer *k* ≥ 3.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] The exponential time hypothesis implies P ≠ NP.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be **exponential time**, if *T*(*n*) is upper bounded by 2poly(*n*), where poly(*n*) is some polynomial in *n*.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] More formally, an algorithm is exponential time if *T*(*n*) is bounded by *O*(2*n**k*) for some constant *k*.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Problems which admit exponential time algorithms on a deterministic Turing machine form the complexity class known as **EXP**.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Sometimes, exponential time is used to refer to algorithms that have *T*(*n*) = 2*O*(*n*), where the exponent is at most a linear function of *n*.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] This gives rise to the complexity class **E**.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be **factorial time** if *T(n)* is upper bounded by the factorial function *n!*.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Factorial time is a subset of exponential time (EXP) because $n!\leq n^{n}=2^{n\log n}=O\left(2^{n^{1+\epsilon }}\right)$ for all $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] An example of an algorithm that runs in factorial time is bogosort, a notoriously inefficient sorting algorithm based on trial and error.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Bogosort sorts a list of *n* items by repeatedly shuffling the list until it is found to be sorted.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] In the average case, each pass through the bogosort algorithm will examine one of the *n*! orderings of the *n* items.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] If the items are distinct, only one such ordering is sorted.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Bogosort shares patrimony with the infinite monkey theorem.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] An algorithm is said to be double exponential time if *T*(*n*) is upper bounded by 22poly(*n*), where poly(*n*) is some polynomial in *n*.
[src:sublinear-algorithms/time-complexity] Such algorithms belong to the complexity class 2-EXPTIME.
